The article discusses the progress made in nuclear security since the first Nuclear Security Summit in 2010. The Obama Administration has focused on nuclear security as part of its comprehensive nuclear policy, which includes nuclear disarmament, nonproliferation, security, and energy. The President identified nuclear terrorism as the most immediate and extreme threat to global security and called for a worldwide effort to secure all vulnerable nuclear materials. The article highlights the successes of the Nuclear Security Summit process, including the removal or elimination of nuclear material, increased security at sites and borders, stronger security practices, and the strengthening of the legal basis for nuclear security. The article also discusses the need to continue enhancing nuclear security, promoting the global nuclear security architecture, and working together to eliminate excess nuclear weapons and material.